² The martyroloyium was, in the earlier times, the register of names of saints and mat-tyrs, which served to bring each successively to the memory of the faithful, on the anniversary of his Passion. At a later period the term denoted, in monastic establish- ments especially, the regist-er more properly called necroloyium, or obituary, wherein were inscribed the obite and benefactione of those who had been received into the fra- ternity of the congregation, and whose names were thus in due course brought to mind, being recited day by day in the chapter, and suitable prayers said. The martyrolog! was termed also uber vitae, and the memorial inscribed annotatio Requloe, because it was generally annexed to the Rule, and connected therewith was the obstuary, wherein the deaths of abbots, priore, and members of the congregation in general, were recorded. The martyr-aloytum occurs next to the requla canonicorum, among the gifts of Bp. Leosric to Exeter, in 1050.
